## 14. Implementation map (where things live)

| Area | Location |
|------|----------|
| Marketing layout + footer | `index.html`, `styles.css`, `script.js` |
| Tool list + anchors | `index.html` `#tools` |
| PDFs | `Presentation/pdf/` |
| Static tool HTML | `Tools/pehchaan_*.html` (e.g. stream advisor, plan B, salary explorer, career assessment, ROI bridge, skill gap, mentor connect, exam roadmap page, **financing reality**) |
| Exam roadmap | `Tools/pehchaan_exam_roadmap.html` and/or `Tools/pehchaan_exam_roadmap/index.html` — verify **relative** `../` paths to `index.html`, `assets/`, and `DB/` from each entry point |
| Tool / product JSON data | `DB/*.json` — keep naming and fetch paths in tools in sync; treat as **content/config** (tone, disclaimers, labels) not bypass for brand rules |
| Logos, icons, shared JS | `assets/` |
| Internal QA / planning docs | `docs/` (do not ship as public pages unless product asks) |
| Parent FAQ app (Next.js) | `parent-faq/` — follow `parent-faq/AGENTS.md` for Next.js version notes |
| Exported parent guide (static) | `Tools/parents-guide/` — prefer editing **`parent-faq/`** then rebuilding/exporting so chrome and copy stay aligned |

**Do not** treat `parent-faq/.next/` as source; it is build output. Prefer `.gitignore` for build artifacts in normal workflows.

When in doubt, **open two surfaces side by side** (marketing header/footer vs tool topbar/footer; primary button; one input) and match them **before** shipping.

---

## 15. Mandatory full-tool UI review protocol (detailed checklist)

Use this section whenever a user asks to review, QA, polish, or align any `Tools/pehchaan_*.html` page (or equivalent Next/export tool surfaces). Do not run a partial visual pass unless explicitly scoped by the user.

### Scope to review every time
- Review **all tool pages**, not just the page currently edited.
- Review each page in both **desktop and mobile-like narrow width**.
- Review each major state where available: default, hover/focus, active/selected, disabled, validation error, and results/summary state.

### A) Tool chrome, logo, and shell parity
- Confirm the top logo area has the approved Pehchaan mark treatment (size, spacing, background, corner radius, and colours) with no distortion.
- Confirm topbar text stack uses the exact brand/title/tagline structure and does not replace the tagline with ad-hoc text.
- Confirm back/home behaviour and relative links are correct for page depth.
- Confirm footer is present and complete in all steps/screens (including wizard sub-steps and result screens).
- Confirm footer has the required three-part content and approved contact strings/order.

### B) Typography and text hierarchy audit
- Verify **Poppins** is consistently used across headings, body, labels, buttons, helper text, disclaimers, and footers.
- Verify font weights follow hierarchy (hero/title > section heading > card title > body > helper/caption).
- Verify line-height and readability for long card text and instruction blocks.
- Verify no oversized or undersized text compared to sibling tools for the same component type.
- Verify capitalization style and punctuation consistency (title case vs sentence case) across repeated UI patterns.

### C) Hero card and all card-level content checks
- Audit hero card visual structure: heading, support text, chips/badges, CTA, and spacing rhythm.
- Audit each card type (info card, form card, result card, warning card, note card) for consistent radius, border, background, and shadow depth.
- Verify text inside cards: heading clarity, concise body copy, no contradictory statements, and no deterministic career promises.
- Verify card internal spacing: padding, spacing between title and text, spacing before/after actions, and consistent vertical rhythm between stacked cards.
- Verify spacing between cards in a section and between sections is consistent and intentional.

### C1) Hero card detailed content standard (mandatory)
Each tool hero card should include a complete, structured content set. Do not ship hero cards that only contain a title.

- **Tool identity line:** clear tool name aligned with the page title and top-level purpose.
- **One-line promise:** what value the student/parent gets from this tool (guidance-oriented, not guarantee-oriented).
- **Who this is for:** short audience qualifier (e.g., Class 10/12 learners, parents, stream switchers, plan-B seekers), if relevant.
- **What you will provide:** 2-4 concise bullets/chips on user inputs needed (interests, marks, budget, location, time horizon, etc.).
- **What you will get:** 2-4 concise bullets/chips on outputs (path options, next steps, skill plan, salary ranges, mentor prompts, etc.).
- **Usage expectation:** quick duration/effort cue (for example: "takes ~3-5 minutes") where appropriate.
- **Action cue:** one primary CTA label that is specific and consistent with flow (e.g., Start analysis, Build my plan, Compare options).
- **Trust/safety cue:** short non-alarmist line that this is guidance for discussion and final decisions need consultation.
- **Language quality:** positive, plain language; avoid jargon-heavy text; avoid deterministic or fear-based phrasing.
- **Length control:** keep hero copy concise; avoid dense paragraphs. Prefer short lines, bullets, chips, and scannable structure.
- **Consistency rule:** hero card message must match downstream section labels, form labels, and result terminology on the same page.
- **No content duplication:** do not repeat the same sentence in hero subtitle, note box, and disclaimer; each line should add unique value.
- **Recommended structure:** intro line + audience cue + `You provide` list + `You get` list + time/effort cue + CTA cue + guidance/safety cue.

### D) Name card / personal detail fields
- Where name inputs exist, ensure labels and placeholders clearly distinguish:
  - First Name
  - Last Name
- Ensure required indicators and validation copy are consistent with the form system.
- Ensure label size, helper text size, and input text size are legible and consistent with other form fields.
- Ensure name cards have the same spacing and control alignment as the rest of the form layout.
- Do not use a single ambiguous `Name` field when the flow expects person details; prefer separate first/last name inputs (optional or required per tool logic).
- For static tool pages, use the **Career ROI name-card pattern** as baseline (`Tools/pehchaan_career_roi_reality_bridge.html`): `name-card` container + lead line + two-column `name-grid` with `First Name` and `Last Name (optional)`.
- Name inputs should follow ROI-style semantics: first name plain label, last name with explicit optional marker, `autocomplete="given-name"` / `autocomplete="family-name"`, and placeholders that look like real names (not generic "Type here").
- Placement rule: when a page has a hero card, keep the name-card **inside the hero card** (not in a later form card) to match Career ROI layout and maintain consistent first-impression structure across tools.

### E) Form controls (dropdowns, text boxes, selectors, pills)
- Dropdowns (`<select>`/custom): verify trigger height, padding, border radius, icon alignment, selected text colour, placeholder styling, and open-state affordance.
- Text boxes (`<input>`, `<textarea>`): verify default/focus/error states, border colours, focus ring strength, placeholder contrast, and cursor/readability.
- Selectors (radio/checkbox/toggle): verify hit area, checked state visibility, keyboard accessibility, and label alignment.
- Pill buttons/chips: verify selected vs unselected states, hover/focus states, spacing between pills, wrapping behaviour, and colour contrast.
- Verify all controls share consistent corner radius and spacing scale unless intentionally differentiated by component role.
- Ensure all user-visible selectable text (dropdown options, button labels, chip labels, and tab labels) uses proper-case presentation and avoids raw snake_case / kebab-case tokens.

### E1) Result-page next tools block standard (mandatory)
- For tool result screens that show onward navigation, use the standardized grouped format:
  1. **Continue Exploring** panel: context-carrying links/chips to related tools.
  2. **What to do next** panel: one primary recommendation and one secondary recommendation, each with short rationale.
- Placement rule (required): on result pages, render this next-tools block near the bottom of the result flow, specifically **just before** the `Important — please read` disclaimer card (not near the top hero/summary).
- Placement rule (required): if adding a support CTA for unresolved queries, place a dedicated contact block **directly above the disclaimer** with helper text like `Did not find what you were looking for?` and a primary button `Still have questions? Reach out to us` linking to Home Contact Us (`../index.html#contact`).
- Preserve contextual helper copy explaining that links pass context but users can still edit on the next page.
- Keep button styling parity with current shared renderer (`assets/pehchaan_tool_recommendations.js`) and avoid one-off ad-hoc card/button variants in individual tools.
- If a tool adds explicit extra links, place them within this grouped structure (not as isolated ungrouped link rows).
- **No self-link rule (required):** the recommendation block must never show the current tool as a suggested link/button (in either **Continue Exploring** or **What to do next**). Always filter out same-tool links before rendering.
- Fit rule (required): linked-tools wrapper and both panels must render as full-width block cards of the parent result area (`display:block; width:100%; box-sizing:border-box;`) and must not shrink to content width inside flex rows.
- Layout guard: when host containers use flex (`.btn-row` or equivalent), linked-tools blocks must force full-row behavior (`flex:1 1 100%; min-width:100%`) so card edges align with sibling result cards.

### F) Disclaimer and important note compliance
- Confirm the mandatory discussion/consultation disclaimer meaning is present in clear language on the first meaningful screen and near results.
- Confirm important disclaimers/notes are visually boxed where required (background, border, icon/emphasis treatment, and readable contrast).
- Confirm disclaimer language is non-deterministic, guidance-oriented, and does not imply guaranteed outcomes.
- Confirm disclaimer placement is prominent (not buried below fold behind optional content).
- Confirm important note/disclaimer spacing separates it from surrounding cards so it reads as a distinct caution block.
- Do **not** duplicate the same disclaimer/note block in the same context/section; keep one canonical block per context and reuse only when the meaning changes by step/state.
- If multiple caution blocks exist on one page, each block must have a distinct purpose (for example, decision clause vs verification/legal note) and must not repeat the same sentence verbatim.

### G) Spacing, layout rhythm, and alignment
- Check section-level spacing consistency: top/bottom margins between hero, forms, cards, notes, and footer.
- Check grid/flex alignment so card edges, form rows, and action groups align cleanly.
- Check responsive wrapping does not cause cramped cards, orphan labels, or uneven padding.
- Check button groups and control rows maintain consistent gaps across breakpoints.
- Flag any one-off spacing value that breaks rhythm unless documented as intentional.
- When two or more tools serve related journeys, normalize their spacing scale (hero-to-card gap, card padding, card-to-card gap, disclaimer spacing, footer separation) unless an intentional exception is documented.

### H) Copy, microcopy, and semantic quality
- Validate all user-facing text for clarity, encouragement, and accuracy with the Pehchaan voice pillars.
- Verify microcopy for fields, helper text, and errors is specific and actionable.
- Ensure hero-card and supporting-card text explains "what this tool does" and "how to use it" in plain language.
- Ensure terms are consistent across tools (e.g., path/stream/career wording).

### I) QA output requirement when asked for review
When delivering a review pass, include:
1. `Visual/Layout deviations` (fonts, cards, spacing, logo, footer, controls)
2. `Copy/Disclaimer deviations` (language, placement, caution-box treatment)
3. `Priority fixes` (high -> medium -> low)
4. `Parity status` per touched tool page (pass / needs fixes)

Treat this checklist as mandatory baseline unless the user explicitly narrows scope.
